Why I've come to value the Curl Up upgrade over Twin Slam:

When I was still doing Downfall Mode runs, I always took the Twin Slam upgrade at the start-of-act fire (except when I boss swapped into Snecko Eye) - my thoughts were that I'd socket the starting gem and then immediately make room for another gem, should I find one I want to socket. Also, the +2 damage upgrade seemed nice, especially since you get that value twice from the Second Slam. Since you want to use the gem anyway, getting the upgraded damage on Twin Slam makes sense.

This approach has merit, but since I moved to Normal(?) mode, I've been forced to wait for the Twin Slam upgrade, as there's no fire on the first floor. As a result, I've been feeling less and less like upgrading Twin Slam early. Naturally, playing Normal mode instead of Downfall mode will mean there's changes in strategy, and this may be influenced by difference in playstyle, but I think the following reasoning is solid to favor Curl Up instead:

What I've noticed is that even despite not having a spare Socket available for Twin Slam, I'm not picking up a second gem for it that quickly. I already don't socket the starting Gem half the time, but even the times I do I still end up waiting a while before I find a good enough second Gem most of the time. Also, Twin Slam+ is only 1 damage more than a strike, so the extra damage I thought I was getting before isn't actually that impactful. I would rather just play strikes than upgrade Twin Slam to do marginally more damage, even with the extra Gem value being offered from inside Twin Slam. So, I ended up just waiting to find the second Gem, and only then would I look for an opportunity to upgrade Twin Slam to fit it in. It's also pretty convenient that the Gems I pick up specifically for Twin Slam are decently strong Gems, which means they're often not even bad to leave unsocketed for a few floors.

I think it also helps that Aquamarine was moved to Uncommon last major patch, so the Dex+Ward combo isn't as easy to get anymore, removing a very strong, easily-available combo from the reasonable possibilities to find quickly.

The other half of this, though, is the hidden value of Curl Up's upgrade. I completely underestimated this upgrade for a long time, but it turns out that both aspects being upgraded are actually really important, even the +2 Brace after the starter relic change to give you an on-demand Brace 10 card to pair with Curl Up.

I've found myself wanting the +2 Brace pretty often, mostly with Roll Attack so far - the ability to enter Defensive Mode with Curl Up+ and Roll Attack means you don't have to play Gear Up & Curl Up, leaving only 1 energy and forfeiting the 16 damage from Roll Attack. That combo is not guaranteed by any means, but it is definitely common enough to happen a decent portion of the time. (There's also 2 other Brace 8 cards, but Shield Spikes is decent block on its own early game, and for Resilient Plate, unless you have a lot of Temp Buff stuff happening already, you might as well play Gear Up, so you're not actually getting an advantage from the +2 Brace upgrade.) Also, reaching 20 Brace in your deck without counting Gear Up means you can enter defensive a __second__ time on the redraw, as 20 + 20 + 10 = 50, how much is needed to enter defensive twice in a fight. Naturally, you could wait until you find Roll Attack to upgrade Curl Up, but there's still the second advantage from upgrading Curl Up:
.

Control over Stasis is a lot more important than it seems. Piloting Guardian well requires good game knowledge of enemy intents, as well as knowledge of what you'll likely be doing on future turns as well. Controlling what cards go into stasis is extremely important for both of these reasons; if you know what the enemy is doing, or have a plan for what you want to do in a couple turns, getting the card that fits your needs in that 2 or 3 turns will save a significant amount of HP, either by saving a block card, or by ending a fight faster by saving a damage card you haven't used yet. Early game, even the difference between having a Strike or Defend can save HP in hallway fights, and control gets even more powerful once you start adding enough cards that are better than strikes and defends that you can save for later.

Also, I _constantly_ find myself having to plan for the case that I play Curl Up and it hits Gear Up at random (unupgraded). I often save Gear Up for the right turn to enter defensive mode, and if I draw Curl Up before that timing hits, Curl Up is getting played first, and it has a 1/5 chance to hit Gear Up, assuming you don't want to guarantee you play certain other cards that turn. 20%+ odds don't sound that bad until you realize it's happening 1 out of every 5 fights on average at worst, so twice in act 1. Missing that defensive mode timing due to Gear Up being somewhere you can't play it means you often take somewhere between 10-15 damage about ***two to three times*** in act 1, which better RNG - or the Curl Up upgrade - would've prevented.

So, all of this is why I think Curl Up is a better first upgrade than Twin Slam. I don't think the Twin Slam upgrade is bad though, and it's often better to play what you're personally comfortable with anyways, as playing outside of your playstyle - even if it turned out that it is the "strictly" better decision - can make you lose more often than just playing how you know to play. Overall though, I highly suggest trying this out over a few runs if you usually go Twin Slam upgrade first and seeing how it feels for yourself.

I think curl up is okay, it's a functional starter card that introduces and plays with some of guardians themes, but it's never exciting, and I have removed it after getting pandoras box before. Putting a random card into stasis from your hand is fairly awkward, making it harder to plan out your turns, and potentially putting an important card you wanted to play this turn into stasis (you can play most of your hand out first to reduce the chance of that happening). Brace 10 is pretty solid for 1 energy, and with the recent update to your starter relic, gets you into your first defensive mode for 2 energy, which can be paid in instalments. If you are planning to do that, you really need to play gear up first, because having curl up put gear up into stasis can cost you a lot of health.

Nearly all of the other cards that place cards into stasis are better than curl up, either having more immediate impact, or putting more/better cards into stasis. I frequently find myself filling up on other stasis cards, and losing that value from curl up going into act 2. Not many other cards can boast about giving 10 brace for 1 energy, though there cards like roll attack or resilient plate that have more utility. It is a notably good card into lagavulin, a bit of a mixed bag against tri-sentries, where you really need to spend energy bursting down an outer sentry early in the fight, but being able to use defensive mode to blur over block can be quite useful later. It's a low impact skill against nob, but can help you blur block over into the big attacks if paired with gear up.

I don't really like the upgrade. Part of that is that I almost never boss swap, so getting 2 extra brace doesn't do much when paired with gear up. Another part is that I find guardian really struggles with dealing enough damage in the early game, and so I want to upgrade attacks instead. I also just don't think that the quality or quantity of tick cards is high enough to warrant it.
I also prioritize the better stasis cards (planning, future plans, recover, reroute) very highly, and so I rarely benefit from the stasis part of curl up anyways.
